00:41.820 --> 00:48.620
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Chad Oliver has never really been able to
devote himself fully to writing science fiction, though he's been publishing it

00:48.620 --> 00:55.740
for over 30 years. He's also a teacher, a professor of anthropology at the
University of Texas at Austin. As is true with many science fiction authors,

00:55.940 --> 01:02.560
Oliver's start as a writer resulted from his fascination with reading science
fiction. As a teenager, he discovered Edgar Rice Burroughs in his lush Martian

01:02.560 --> 01:11.380
stories and tried to get his hands on everything Burroughs published. Because of
the addiction to Burroughs, one time when I was in a newsstand, I saw a copy of

01:11.380 --> 01:26.220
the big old fat Amazing Stories. It had a cover story by Burroughs called Tiger
Girl, and also a story by Eando Binder. You remember him? Or rather, you

01:26.220 --> 01:35.480
remember them, Earl and Otto, called Adam Link Saves the World. Anyway, I bought
the copy of Amazing because I wanted to read the Burroughs story, and I figured,

01:35.560 --> 01:46.280
well, I might as well read all this other stuff, too. And there was a story in
there by Edmond Hamilton called Treasure on Thunder Moon, which I read and was

01:46.280 --> 01:54.380
immediately hooked. I thought this was, you know, the greatest thing I had ever
read, maybe the greatest thing anybody had ever written. And I decided, well, by

01:54.380 --> 02:05.920
golly, the thing to be is to be a professional writer and to write science
fiction. And I got a second-hand portable typewriter, and I taught myself to

02:05.920 --> 02:20.720
type, and I wrote something every week between the time I was 14 and when I was
21 when I sold my first story, and sent it all off. Editors were just immensely

02:20.720 --> 02:32.440
helpful. I never got form rejection slips, even at 14 years old. And you can
imagine the kind of junk you were writing at 14. But people like Sam Merwin, for

02:32.440 --> 02:42.180
example, would write me little notes, you know, we can't use this but keep
trying and so forth. And in effect, what really happened was that I got hooked

02:42.180 --> 02:53.800
on science fiction, and I just thought science fiction writers must be gods, and
I wanted to be one. And I figured that's as close to a god as I could get. So I

02:53.800 --> 02:58.720
went at it, and I kept writing until I sold my first story. And I've sold every
one I've written since.

03:06.240 --> 03:13.120
But Oliver was also pursuing an academic career, and he took a master's degree
in English from the University of Texas. His master's thesis was written on

03:13.120 --> 03:19.860
magazine science fiction, the first academic thesis written on that particular
subject. With a degree in English, you might have expected Oliver to become an

03:19.860 --> 03:30.960
English teacher or a full-time writer of science fiction. We asked him why he
didn't become either. Actually, I was briefly. After I got my MA, I taught

03:30.960 --> 03:41.820
English at the university for one year. And there were two troubles that were
involved in that situation. From my point of view, I don't know what troubles

03:41.820 --> 03:53.200
the students had. But the two troubles were basically that by the time I had
started to teach English, I was so much into anthropology that I already knew

03:53.200 --> 04:04.580
that that's what I wanted to do. And I really was just teaching the English
because I had told Ransom I would. And the other aspect of it was there's

04:04.580 --> 04:13.160
nothing like teaching freshman English for a year to convince you that that's
not what you want to do for the rest of your life. So that was the end of it. I

04:13.160 --> 04:22.120
left, then went to UCLA to graduate school in anthropology. I know that doesn't
answer the question about why I didn't become a full-time professional writer,

04:23.020 --> 04:34.620
but I'm not sure I can answer that question. And Tony Boucher once said to me,
sooner or later, you're going to have to choose. And I never did. And I suppose

04:34.620 --> 04:44.540
that one reason was that I was, particularly at that time, when I was, you know,
100 years younger than I am now, I was just as interested in anthropology as I

04:44.540 --> 04:54.600
was in writing. And I really wanted to teach anthropology. And so I tried to do
both, doubtless, within different success. More with science fiction author Chad

04:54.600 --> 04:55.420
Oliver next time.

