Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:16.960 --> 06:22.280
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:24.980 --> 06:26.620
And here are your hosts.

06:30.480 --> 06:38.480
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Chad Oliver has been publishing science
fiction for more than three decades. His novels include Shadows in the Sun, The

06:38.480 --> 06:44.960
Winds of Time, The Shores of Another Sea, and Giants in the Dust. He's also had
a couple of short story collections published, but he's always had to do his

06:44.960 --> 06:52.620
writing in his spare time. Professional anthropologist. He teaches anthropology
at the University of Texas at Austin, and he's also chairman of the anthropology

06:52.620 --> 07:05.480
department. Actually, I was chairman of the department of anthropology from 1967
to 1971. And when I resigned, I swore I would never do it again under any

07:05.480 --> 07:19.020
circumstances whatsoever. And so here I am in the third year of my second
chairmanship, and I figure I've got one year to go, and then somebody else is

07:19.020 --> 07:27.680
going to take over. And hopefully I can get back to writing, not on a full-time
basis, but I can sure write more than I can when I'm tied up with the

07:27.680 --> 07:35.700
chairmanship. It's really a full-time job. With a distinguished career at the
University, Oliver still spends time writing science fiction. We asked him why?

07:36.060 --> 07:50.580
For the money? No, I really think that writing is something you have to do. And
at any rate, that's the way it is with me. When I go a certain length of time

07:50.580 --> 08:03.980
without writing anything or trying to write something, I get actually physically
uncomfortable. And it's definitely a labor of love. I think of myself as an

08:03.980 --> 08:14.520
anthropologist who occasionally writes a story. I think that way down the
street, wherever it is I really live, what I am is a writer who got interested

08:14.520 --> 08:26.880
in anthropology rather than the other way around. And it means more to me, I
think. It's more gratifying to me than anything else I'd say. I just told a

08:26.880 --> 08:42.980
story to Analog, a story called "Ghost Town". It's going to be out in either the
September or October issue. And I was thrilled when Analog did it. And it's

08:42.980 --> 08:50.820
almost like I'd never told a story before. And it's infinitely important than
the other things that I did to me.

08:58.220 --> 09:05.360
Oliver is recognized for his use of anthropology and science fiction, and is
probably the first science fiction author to do so. He's even had one of his

09:05.360 --> 09:15.500
novels, Shadows in the Sun, reviewed in an anthropology journal. We asked him if
the use of anthropology was deliberate. To some extent, but it was certainly

09:15.500 --> 09:25.760
nothing that I sat down and planned. You know, like, here's an effective way to
teach anthropology, that I'm going to do it through science fiction. I really

09:25.760 --> 09:35.520
think that the actual truth of the situation is that any writer writes about all
the things that they know. And one of the things that I knew was anthropology.

09:36.020 --> 09:47.200
So it's more or less natural that a fair amount of my opinion is rooted in
anthropology. But by no means all of it. And it's too short of it. Particularly

09:47.200 --> 09:58.920
the stories that I like the most. I don't know whether anybody else likes it. It's kind of a story that doesn't have 
to be about anthropology at all. Although, you know, I don't even go on about this.

10:01.740 --> 10:08.700
But at the point of the influence that you can frequently ask much at the same time,

10:08.700 --> 10:09.480
and I'm just going to start with a question.

10:10.440 --> 10:12.660
Among them, what does it mean to be human?

10:13.300 --> 10:15.220
Where are we going and where are we going?

10:16.320 --> 10:24.520
And it seems to me that if you're involved seriously in the field, you tend to fall into the other one.

10:25.500 --> 10:30.040
I would guess, I don't know whether anybody's ever actually counted it up.

10:23.300 --> 10:40.360
But I suppose something like 50% of my
perhaps is rooted directly in anthropology. But 50% it isn't. We'll continue

10:40.360 --> 10:41.900
talking with Chad Oliver on our next show.

10:48.840 --> 10:56.680
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
