12:39.960 --> 12:47.760
The idea is to have mankind start fresh, to see if he'll make the same mistakes
or take some alternate evolutionary path. With that plan in mind, the humans are

12:47.760 --> 12:55.380
left on the planet with no technological aid whatsoever. Varnum himself is a
throwback, a tough hunter who hasn't succumbed to the softness and lethargy of

12:55.380 --> 13:01.900
the rest of humanity. When the humans reach the point where they begin to
domesticate animals and practice agriculture, Varnum stops them. We asked Oliver

13:01.900 --> 13:10.040
why. Wouldn't Varnum's action and effect prevent civilization from developing?
Well, actually, the funny thing about Giants in the Dust, there are lots of

13:10.040 --> 13:20.160
funny things about Giants in the Dust, including the fact that that's not my
title. And I haven't the faintest idea of what Giants in the Dust means in the

13:20.160 --> 13:30.860
context of that particular novel. I called it Go Back, Go Back. But it's about a
kind of anthropology that most people are not familiar with. You know, almost

13:30.860 --> 13:43.920
all the anthropology in science fiction comes out, really, of the old Franz Boas
Ruth Benedict cultural relativism position. And there's a whole new school in

13:43.920 --> 13:54.460
anthropology, if you can call it a school, and not just in anthropology, because
it gets into sociobiology and all sorts of things, which states, in effect, you

13:54.460 --> 14:03.820
know, that there's more to human beings at birth than just being the traditional
tabula rasa, that there's some things built in. And what I was trying to do in

14:03.820 --> 14:14.420
Giants in the Dust, or what was going on there, was really to take the old deal
about, suppose you took 50 people, 25 male, 25 female, and you cast them away on

14:14.420 --> 14:25.540
the traditional desert island. What would happen to them if they could somehow
survive from infancy and grow into adulthood? And one possibility that hasn't

14:25.540 --> 14:37.920
been considered is that we have a kind of culture-building device within us, and
that we would recreate a good deal of culture much more quickly than is usually

14:37.920 --> 14:50.680
assumed. And I was playing around with that idea in Giants in the Dust. And the
reason why Varnum stops these various inventions and things is because he wants

14:50.680 --> 15:01.520
to give it time to unfold to see what will happen. But you may recall Varnum's
the only character in the book who retains any memory. And at the end of the

15:01.520 --> 15:13.500
book, he finally decides that ethically, the only thing he can do is to tell
him, tell the other people, what he remembers of the culture back on Earth, and

15:13.500 --> 15:17.500
to give them a fair shot at what's going on.

15:27.400 --> 15:38.460
We should not have developed our present civilization with its high level of
technology. No, I wasn't. I think you can construct an argument to the effect

15:38.460 --> 15:49.380
that people in other kinds of societies, particularly hunting and gathering
societies, have some things that we don't have. It's not all one-sided.

15:49.800 --> 16:01.640
Civilization is not an unmixed blessing. And people who live in those band
type of societies, they tend to be freer from stress. They tend to have fewer

16:01.640 --> 16:13.600
emotional problems than people who live in societies such as our own. And so I
don't think it's a completely insane argument to say, you know, maybe we'd all

16:13.600 --> 16:23.620
be better off if we were still hunters and gatherers. But no, it's not a
position I would advocate because I don't think it's a, it's not a realistic

16:23.620 --> 16:28.660
proposition outside the world of fantasy. More with Chad Oliver next time.

16:35.700 --> 16:43.580
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
