17:57.400 --> 17:59.100
And here are your hosts.

18:03.220 --> 18:11.060
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. In a recent science fiction story, Chad
Oliver raises an interesting question. Can man colonize in space? Well, the human

18:11.060 --> 18:18.260
race split into two separate species, spacers and earthers. The story is
entitled, "Meanwhile Back on the Reservation", and has appeared in the 1981

18:18.260 --> 18:25.680
edition of Analog Magazine. As the title suggests, Earth becomes sort of a
reservation containing the backwash of human culture, while the other worlds,

18:25.760 --> 18:32.760
colonized by humans, become the progressive mainstream of mankind's culture. We
asked Oliver if he thought such a situation could occur as we move out into

18:32.760 --> 18:47.060
space. I think it's possible. I think it's possible. Really, the genesis of,
meanwhile, back on the reservation was twofold. And one was simply the kind of

18:47.060 --> 18:58.100
reaction that builds up in you when everybody talks about, hey, you know, here's
the glorious future coming onward to the stars, everybody. When you stop and

18:58.100 --> 19:13.000
realize everybody's not going. And in fact, 99.99% of the human population will
live and die on this planet. And you've got to wonder, well, what about them?

19:13.260 --> 19:25.180
Aren't they people too? And it's anthropological, I think, primarily in the
sense of they're in the same boat that so-called primitive peoples are on this

19:25.180 --> 19:38.060
planet today. That the march of culture, for want of another term, has passed
them by to some extent. And they're sort of islands that are left in the stream

19:38.060 --> 19:48.380
and left behind. And yet they have all the problems of living the face that
anybody else does. And I was just trying to raise the question, well, all right,

19:48.460 --> 19:56.480
what about the people who stay behind? Do we just write them off? Are they
ciphers? Or aren't they just as important as somebody that goes off to Alpha

19:56.480 --> 19:57.820
Centaurus or someplace?

20:03.560 --> 20:10.260
Oliver's been publishing science fiction for over 30 years. And for a good part
of that time, he's lived in Austin, Texas, and taught anthropology at the

20:10.260 --> 20:16.800
University of Texas. Oliver goes on to talk about Meanwhile Back on the
Reservation and reveals some interesting information about his background as a

20:16.800 --> 20:25.440
science fiction writer and also about science fiction writers in Texas. The
other thing that was involved in that story was that I had not written any short

20:25.440 --> 20:41.020
fiction in a while. And I got mixed up with the Turkey City Group in Austin,
which has been a source of untold joy in my life. And a number of people who

20:41.020 --> 20:51.260
were involved in that group, Lisa Tuttle and Howard Waldrop and a number of
others, had urged me to try to do something again, not wait so long between

20:51.260 --> 21:04.040
stories. And meanwhile, back on the reservations, actually the first story I
ever wrote that I submitted to a criticism from other writers. And I learned a

21:04.040 --> 21:15.580
lot from them. And it was a very rewarding experience. And I can't tell you what
a thrill it is for me to be living in some place like Austin and to find a whole

21:15.580 --> 21:25.240
colony of professional science fiction writers there. And not just there, but
the fact that they're so good. You know, for something like 20 years, I was all

21:25.240 --> 21:34.120
alone in Texas. The closest thing there was to a science fiction convention or
gathering in the old days was when Walt Miller and I got together for a six-pack

21:34.120 --> 21:47.020
of beer in Kyle. And this is a brand-new experience for me. And it's comparable
only to the situation I was in when I was in Los Angeles in graduate school. And

21:47.020 --> 21:56.520
Ray Bradbury and Chuck Beaumont and Bill Nolan and Dick Matheson and all of us
would get together and talk about stories. But we never criticized each other's

21:56.520 --> 22:05.060
manuscripts in a more or less formal session like that. Instead, you know,
somebody would write something, and if there was somebody they liked, they'd

22:05.060 --> 22:13.500
take a, hey, look at this, you know, you think I can do anything with it. And
then 20 years more or less by myself, really. More next time with Chad Oliver.

