23:48.140 --> 23:56.220
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. The Shores of Another Sea, Chad Oliver's
1971 science fiction novel, was partially based on the author's experience when

23:56.220 --> 24:03.720
he did some anthropological research in Africa. The novel concerns alien
contact, a standard science fiction theme. The contact is made when some aliens

24:03.720 --> 24:11.060
land in a remote area of Africa. And the aliens are very cautious. They don't
present themselves to humans. They use baboons at first, studying them and

24:11.060 --> 24:18.220
taking over their bodies in order to approach men without being detected. But a
man named Royce Crawford, a scientist studying the baboons, becomes aware of the

24:18.220 --> 24:25.600
aliens' presence. He can't go for help, though, because a storm washes out the
roads and isolates him from civilization. We asked Oliver if the setting was

24:25.600 --> 24:42.780
based on the time he spent in Africa. Yes, it was. The Shores of Another Sea is
at least rooted in the 17 months or so that I spent in Kenya in East Africa when

24:42.780 --> 24:57.860
I was on a research job with a people called the Kamba. And some aspects of The
Shores of Another Sea are real. Some are invented, as is true in any fiction.

24:58.140 --> 25:12.640
But to be specific, the storm and the rains and the isolation that form a major
part of The Shores of Another Sea, that all happened. And I was marooned for a

25:12.640 --> 25:23.280
period of some weeks at what was that? I forget what I called it in the novel. I
may even have used its real name, which was the Derajani Research Station. And

25:23.280 --> 25:35.900
when those rains came down, they simply knocked out all communications. And the
thought just occurred to me. You know, suppose you were going to contact this

25:35.900 --> 25:46.900
Earth and you had to begin somewhere. Would you really plunk your ship down in
the middle of New York City the way they always do? Or would you try it first in

25:46.900 --> 25:56.240
a controllable type of situation where you could deal with small numbers and
related species? And wouldn't it be interesting if you started off with some

25:56.240 --> 26:05.700
other form of primate like a baboon? And that's where The Shores of Another Sea
came from. But if you go back and read the book, or at least if I go back and

26:05.700 --> 26:15.020
look at it, what I see are all kinds of detailed memories of what actually
happened in Kenya, right down to the level of the pipe tobacco I was smoking

26:15.020 --> 26:20.100
there, which was called Sweet Nut and came in a yellow tin and was perfectly
awful.

26:30.440 --> 26:37.620
At one point in the novel, Royce Crawford has a huge water buck in the sights of
his rifle. He's always dreamed of shooting this animal, but he chooses not to.

26:37.860 --> 26:49.800
We asked Oliver if Crawford's decision resulted from his experiences with the
aliens. Sure. The scene in which the would-be hunter finally has a chance to

26:49.800 --> 27:02.600
shoot the animal that he's always dreamed about and elects to let it go free,
that's an analog of what is going on in the rest of the book as well, which is

27:02.600 --> 27:14.680
you have an opportunity or you encounter aliens, and if you simply treat them
the way one human being hopefully might treat another under the best of

27:14.680 --> 27:26.740
circumstances, maybe this kind of encounter is going to hold more promise than
either a situation where they come out with ray guns blasting or one where

27:26.740 --> 27:39.840
there's some involved Machiavellian plot. The notion that I was really playing
around with there was simply maybe the level of communication is going to have

27:39.840 --> 27:50.480
to take place on the level of, look, there's some good in us, there's some good
in you, let's try to find the common ground. This show ends our week with Chad

27:50.480 --> 27:56.560
Oliver. If you're interested in further discussions with him, keep listening to
the Science Fiction Radio Show. We'll be talking with him again in the future.

28:03.980 --> 28:11.960
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

